<DOC><DOCNO> AP900909-0048 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-09-90 2115EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-NYCPoll     09-09 0220</FIRST><SECOND>AM-NYC Poll,0225</SECOND><HEAD>Most New Yorkers Say You Have to Be a Little Crazy</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Summer of Crime, Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Six out of 10 New Yorkers say they would liveelsewhere if they could, and three-quarters describe the city asdangerous and dirty, according to a poll published Sunday.   The Time magazine-Cable News Network poll asked 1,009 residents:``If you could choose where you live, would you stay in New YorkCity or move somewhere else?'' According to the results, 59 percentwould be ex-New Yorkers, and 37 percent would stay.   The poll, conducted Aug. 2-5, has a margin of error of plus orminus 3 percent.   Asked if the quality of life had become better in the past fewyears, 7 percent said yes. Sixty-eight percent said things wereworse.   Twice as many New Yorkers said things would get still worse assaid things would get better _ 45 percent to 23 percent.   Asked if New York was dirty, 78 percent said yes. Dangerous?Yes, said 73 percent. On the other hand, 54 percent described NewYork as a city they like to live in.   That may be explained by the response to the statement: ``Tolive in New York City, people must be a little crazy.'' More thanhalf _ 52 percent _ agreed.</TEXT></DOC>